Nicholas Basell of Diirkheim, W. of Mannheim, was a monk at Hirsau‚ a Benedictine abbey near Calw in Wiirtemberg‚ where his life was mainly spent. Pellican saw him there in 1496 (CPR. p. 44), at which time Trithemius‚ whose pupil Basell was in Spanheim at some period, was also in Hirsau. In June 1505 Basell may be traced at Spires (TE. ii. 15); on 1 Sept. 1508 he finished copying a MS. of Reuchlin's Colloquia Graeca at Hirsau (Stuttgart MS. poet. 76); and he was still a monk there in 1520, when he is described as ‘venerabilis pater’ (BRE. 179 and 207). He continued the chronicle of Nauclerus (Ep. 397) down to 15143 but K. E. H.
